  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">\"Islamic Glass in the Making,\" published by Leuven University Press in 2022, represents a significant contribution to the understanding of Islamic art and history. While currently, it shows limited academic citations and public engagement metrics, its potential relevance in sustainability and policy is underscored by its commercial availability on platforms like Amazon and Goodreads.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The book \"Islamic Glass in the Making,\" published in 2022, stands as an informative resource in the field of Islamic art history. Despite the lack of citations and public discourse metrics at this time, the book\u2019s commercial availability on platforms such as Amazon and Goodreads indicates a proactive approach to reaching wider audiences. This commercial linkage suggests that the work could foster interest beyond academic circles, emphasizing its potential contribution to public understanding of Islamic artifacts.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">In addition to its commercial outreach, the book has been linked to sustainability and policy insights, as indicated by a moderate strength of 0.55 in this area. This connection to broader societal themes reinforces the idea that the study of Islamic glass is not merely an academic pursuit but bears relevance to contemporary discussions about cultural heritage and environmental sustainability.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The book shows potential for scholarly uptake with a strength of 0.45, hinting at its future impact on the academic community. As scholars increasingly look for interdisciplinary connections within the humanities, this work may soon find itself cited as a reference point for subsequent studies on art historical practices in Islamic cultures.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">As the landscape of academic publishing evolves, \"Islamic Glass in the Making\" may still benefit from enhanced visibility. Its current positioning shifts the focus on the ways in which it can seed future discussions in Islamic art and cultural studies, potentially bridging gaps between commercial interests and scholarly inquiry.</p>",
